I just realised while thinking about version 2 that class decorators are the only way to define composite decorators (for arbitrary text replacement).

I imagine these could be turned into dicts, following what Draft.js does (https://draftjs.org/docs/advanced-topics-decorators.html#compositedecorator), a pattern somewhat similar to that of the block definitions:

```js
{
    // A function in Draft.js (using a regex or anything else) – could just be the regex for the exporter.
    strategy: hashtagStrategy,
    // A React component in Draft.js – Python function in our case.
    // Should be called `element` if we followed the same pattern as the block deifinitions and also supported using tags directly.
    component: HashtagSpan,
},
```

This is a bit more work than just removing those conditionals in `DOM.render`.

Oh and in terms of performance, the gain seems to be 2-6% from early testing using the new benchmark (literally every block, style, entity, piece of text goes through these conditionals, and the checks are ordered from least to most common).

