One can always write a specific script + parameterized root config json for his/her own specific purpose and can do all the things as I show above.

The point of my script is to not have to write specific parameterized root config or specifc script. But rather have generalized way of configuring what one wants to explore by defining only one config.
This includes: what keys will be set to what value, names and (not included yet) evaluation datasets to explore, analyse and report these generated sub-experiment configs on. All things pertaining to
train / evaluate / analyse / report explorations of the root experiment in **one** place (and **separate** from root config).

An equivalent config for above command would be:

```json
{

  "combine_changes": [
      {
      "key_tuple": ["model.title_encoder.bidirectional", "model.abstract_encoder.bidirectional"],
      "value_tuples": [
                   ["true", "true"],
                   ["false", "false"]
                ],
      }
      {
      "key_tuple": ["model.text_field_embedder.tokens.trainable"],
      "value_tuples": [
                   ["true"],
                   ["false"],
                ],
      }
      {
      "key_tuple": ["model.title_encoder.type"],
      "value_tuples": [
                   ["'gru'"],
                   ["'lstm'"],
                ],
      }
  ]
}
```

and would not require any specific parameterization / variable defining / changes in root config. It is self-sufficient and quite succinct on what one wants to explore starting from a root config.

If I compare your way and mine, main difference is:

- I decide what key will be set to what value in one separate config.
- You define variables in one config (SUB), pass variables in to root config and leave decision of what key to set to what value in root config.

If you make a generally usable script out of your script, it will need to take 2 inputs: SUB like config file and parameterized root config both of which will have to be configured specific to one's requirement.
Although your is simple implementation-wise, I think this PR one is easier to use. If you think otherwise, I would be fine closing this ....

