@kovidgoyal I would actually add a way to fall back to threads if it is not possible to use INotify. It is not needed to trade off complete coverage in this case, as well as it is not needed to trade off efficiency.

Though under current circumstances I think it is better to have another watcher type, rather then resurrect previous version. By “another watcher” I mean the one which will use INotify/pyuv and if that fails then stat-based, but with support for recursive watching; the last one must be run in the separate thread and periodically query the filesystem so that it will not slow things down on filesystems like sshfs.

The thing that bothers me most is pyuv missing some filesystem events for unknown reason, at least on linux. Have not heard the same for Windows or Mac OS (which was the reason to add it), but maybe users just have not noticed.

// If you are wondering why I did not yet add at least a PR with that watcher type: this idea came up only now, during the discussion. I think it is better then previous idea of falling back to threads and yet should function well enough.

@jtillman You can prevent marshmallow from storing your generated classes in its internal registry of schemas by generating the classes without a name.

```python
class ResponseObject(Schema):
    @classmethod
    def load_paged_result(cls, data):
        fields = {
            'page_number': fields.Integer(),
            'total': fields.Integer(),
            'items': fields.List(fields.Nested(cls)),
        }
        attrs = dict(fields, Meta=Meta)
        # Create a nameless class to prevent storing the class in
        # marshmallow's in-memory registry
        ResponsePageObject = type(str(''), (ma.Schema,), attrs)
        return ResponsePageObject(strict=True).loads(data)

class UserResponse(ResponseObject):
    name = fields.String()
```

I've also proposed #660 , which would expose a more straightforward way to bypass the registry. In the meantime, the above workaround should get you most of the way.

I can envision the use of dot notation in the `@validator` decorator.

```python
class Person(Schema):
    age = fields.Integer()

    # I don't want to specify a validator here.
    # This schema is a "base" one. It maps
    # directly to a DB model.


class BuyJuice(Schema):
    customer = fields.Nested(Person)

    # This is the website form (or API method)
    # to buy orange juice. No need to validate
    # the customer's age.


class BuyAlcohol(Schema):
    customer = fields.Nested(Person)

    @validator('customer.age')
    def min_age(self, value):
        # 21 years to purchase

    # Here the age validation is mandatory,
    # but it has nothing to do with the
    # Person schema itself.
```

